Scala.name: PolygonFractal

Python.name: PolygonFractal
Python.correction:
# BEGIN TEMPLATE
def polygonFractal (levels, sides, length, shrink):
    # BEGIN SOLUTION
    if (levels == 0):
      pass
    else:
      for i in range(sides):
        forward(length)
        
        left((sides-2)*360/(sides*2))
        polygonFractal(levels-1, sides, length*shrink,shrink)
        right((sides-2)*360/(sides*2))
        right(360/sides)
    # END SOLUTION
# END TEMPLATE 

polygonFractal(getParam(0),getParam(1),getParam(2),getParam(3))

initialWorlds.name: polygonFractal(1,5,100,0.5)
initialWorlds.about:
The universe of turtles

This is an adaptation of LOGO for the Programmer's Learning Machine.

It is directly inspired from the work of the mathematician Seymour Papert in the 60's. Inspired from the swiss psycholog Jean Piaget, he came up with a learning method called LOGO to teach programming to young childs. The world is full of turtles which leave a painting where they go and which respond to simple orders.

Functions to move the turtle

void forward(double steps)
void backward(double steps)
Moves forward or backward of the requested amount of steps. 
void right(double angle)
void left(double angle)
Turns left or right of the given angle (in degrees). 
double getX()
double getY()
Returns the current position of the turtle. Note that the point (0,0) is on the top left corner, as it is often the case in Computer Science. 
void setX(double x)
void setY(double y)
void setPos(double x, double y)
Teleports the turtle to a new position (without leaving any trace). 
void moveTo(double x, double y)
Moves the turtle to a new position. 
void circle(double radius)
Draw a circle of the specified radius centered on the turtle. 
void hide()
Hides the turtle. 
void show()
Shows the turtle back. 
boolean isVisible()
Returns whether the turtle is currently visible. 
void clear()
Removes any trail on the sheet. 
double getHeading()
Returns the current heading of the turtle (in degrees). 
void setHeading(double angle)
Sets a new heading to the turtle (in degrees).

Functions about the pen

void penUp()
Moves the pen up (turtles have pens, not brushes as buggles). The turtle will not leave any trace during its subsequent moves. 
void penDown()
Moves the pen down. The turtle will leave a trace during its subsequent moves. 
boolean isPenDown()
Returns the current pen position as a boolean. 
Color getColor()
Returns the current pen color. 
void setColor(Color color)
Changes the pen color.

Other functions

boolean isSelected()
Returns whether the current turtle is selected in the graphical interface.

Valid colors

answerWorlds.about:
The universe of turtles

This is an adaptation of LOGO for the Programmer's Learning Machine.

It is directly inspired from the work of the mathematician Seymour Papert in the 60's. Inspired from the swiss psycholog Jean Piaget, he came up with a learning method called LOGO to teach programming to young childs. The world is full of turtles which leave a painting where they go and which respond to simple orders.

Functions to move the turtle

void forward(double steps)
void backward(double steps)
Moves forward or backward of the requested amount of steps. 
void right(double angle)
void left(double angle)
Turns left or right of the given angle (in degrees). 
double getX()
double getY()
Returns the current position of the turtle. Note that the point (0,0) is on the top left corner, as it is often the case in Computer Science. 
void setX(double x)
void setY(double y)
void setPos(double x, double y)
Teleports the turtle to a new position (without leaving any trace). 
void moveTo(double x, double y)
Moves the turtle to a new position. 
void circle(double radius)
Draw a circle of the specified radius centered on the turtle. 
void hide()
Hides the turtle. 
void show()
Shows the turtle back. 
boolean isVisible()
Returns whether the turtle is currently visible. 
void clear()
Removes any trail on the sheet. 
double getHeading()
Returns the current heading of the turtle (in degrees). 
void setHeading(double angle)
Sets a new heading to the turtle (in degrees).

instructions.en:
Fractal of polygons

The fractal we will now draw is formed of a polygon, with little polygons on each corner. The prototype of the method drawing it is the following: 
[!java|c]void [/!]polygonFractal ([!java|c]int [/!]levels[!scala]:Int[/!], [!java|c]int [/!]sides[!scala]:Int[/!], [!java|c]double [/!]length[!scala]:Double[/!], [!java|c]double [/!]shrink[!scala]:Double[/!])

Have a look at each world's objective view to understand how to write the function.
instructions.fr:
Fractales de polygones

La fractale que nous allons dessiner maintenant est forme d'un polygone auquel sont ajouts des petits polygones sur chaque angle. Le prototype de la fonction le traant est le suivant: 
[!java|c]void [/!]polygonFractal ([!java|c]int [/!]niveaux[!scala]:Int[/!], [!java|c]int [/!]cots[!scala]:Int[/!], [!java|c]double [/!]longueur[!scala]:Double[/!], [!java|c]double [/!]multiplicateur[!scala]:Double[/!])

Consultez les objectifs de chaque monde pour comprendre comment crire la fonction.
